question:
Three lines \(L_1\), \(L_2\), and \(L_3\) are given by the equations:

\[
\begin{aligned}

L_{1}: & \vec{r}=\lambda \hat{i}, \lambda \in \mathbb{R}, \\

L_{2}: & \vec{r}=a\hat{k}+b\hat{j}, a, b \in \mathbb{R} \text { and } \\

L_{3}: & \vec{r}=\hat{i}+\hat{j}+c\hat{k}, c \in \mathbb{R}

\end{aligned}
\]

For which point(s) \(Q\) on \(L_2\) can we find a point \(P\) on \(L_1\) and a point \(R\) on \(L_3\) so that \(P, Q\) and \(R\) are collinear?

Let $g(x)$ be a function defined on the interval $(0,1)$. The function is given as follows:

      g(x) = {(x^2 - 3x + 2), if x is rational}
            {(4x^2 - 2x + 1), if x is irrational}
